We can repeat this procedure with a larger number of strips. Figure 6 shows what hap-
pens when we divide the region S into eight strips of equal width. By computing the sum
of the1  arR8 2eas of the smaller rectangles 1L8 2 and the sum of the areas of the larger rectan-gles , we obtain better lower and upper estimates for A:
0.2734375 % A % 0.3984375
So one possible answer to the question is to say that the true area of S lies somewhere be-
tween 0.2734375 and 0.3984375.
